Syntax for quasiquotes (ALREADY DECENT QUALITY!)

In line with Martin's SID "String interpolation and formatting", I've implemented a syntax for qq's:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NdxNxZYodPA-c4MLr33KzwzKFkzm9iW9POexT9PkJsU/edit?hl=en_US

The machinery described in the SID has been generalized to allow for
arbitrary quasiquotes, not only for string interpolations.

The main difference from the proposal is using the newly introduced Quasiquote class from scala.reflect:
  class Quasiquote(parts: List[String], splices: List[Code[_]], formats: List[String])
and transforming quasiquotes into an intermediate representation that involves Quasiquote and that
can be processed in a domain-specific way later on, by a quasiquoting macro.

For example,
  s"hello $s"
will be transformed into
  val parts = Apply(Ident(ListModule), List(Literal(Constant("hello ")), Literal(Constant(""))))
  val splices = Apply(Ident(ListModule), Ident(newTermName("s")))
  val formats = Apply(Ident(ListModule), List(Literal(Constant(""))))
  val ctor = New(Ident(QuasiquoteLiteralClass), List(parts, splices, formats))
  Apply(Select(ctor, newTermName("s")), List())

In this commit, I've injected a hack into doTypedApply that detects calls to s()
and manually assembles string interpolation logic. Later on, the typer will resolve "s"
to be an extension macro for Quasiquote and will invoke that macro, which, in its turn,
will produce the glue that involves StringContext and Formatted as mentioned in the SID.

pull_request.title: More stream-lined approach to wrap extension points

repo.name: jenkins-plugin-runtime.rb
repo.description: The idomatic Ruby API for building Jenkins CI plugins

pull_request.body:
Jenkins defines two kinds of extension points. One is for thing like Builder and Publisher, where we get a lot of instances created and retained in a single JVM. This is `Descriptor` and `Describable` and we've already got a proven mechanism to define more wrappers.

The other kind, which is actually more fundamental, is a mechanism for Jenkins to discover singleton instances that are the extension points, such as `EnvironmentContributor`, `RunListener`, and `PageDecorator` (`Descriptor` is actually just one of these, and `Describable` is just a further layer above.)

This pull request adds a mechanism for us to rapidly define such singleton extension points.

The main change is the `ExtensionPoint` module, which is a mix-in that detects subtype implementations, and it'll invoke a callback specified via the `when_implemented` class method. I've added a couple of actual wrappers based on this mechanism (and used them successfuly in the RVM plugin.)

One thing that I couldn't quite figure out was how to modify `Jenkins::Model::Describable` to use `ExtensionPoint` to avoid dupliation of the subtype detection logic. I'll think more about it later.

pull_request.title: Some tweaks to allow client-side to work?
pull_request.body:
Hey again!

I made some changes to the structure of the requires to remove circular references (e.g., Liquid refers to Liquid.Block, which refers to Liquid).  I introduced a "liquid_base" file that is the initial definitions of the Liquid class that both the final Liquid module and the block, tags, etc. refers to.

I also moved the work to load tags into a function and wrapped a try/catch around it since there is no fs module on the client-side.

By doing this, using browserify actually works!  I generated a **liquify.js**  that you can find in https://github.com/tchype/node-liquify in the public/javascripts folder.

By running the app.js with node and opening http://localhost:8125 in your browser, you can see liquid working a little bit, fully client-side!

Hopefully this isn't too ugly, because it's a **HUGE HELP** and made all the difference in getting it to work client-side.

Thanks again!  Nice work, man.  It only took me like 1-2 days total to go from nothing to seeing liquid working in the browser.  Remarkable.  You did a _great_ job.  
Tony

Removed CharArray. Use ByteArray in String.

Initially, the thought was that a CharArray could encapsulate the idea of a
vector of bytes and the interpretation of those bytes relative to a particular
encoding scheme. However, in practice, the interpretation of those bytes is
really encapsulated in String, which composes a ByteArray and an Encoding.
Pushing the logic down into CharArray required delegating almost everything
from String, which is a good indicator for a poor abstraction.

One example in particular illustrates this: a ByteArray (and CharArray)
contain a boundary-aligned number of bytes, the boundary being a machine word.
The size of a ByteArray (CharArray) is always >= to the number of bytes needed
for a String's data. Encoding operations need to operate on the precise number
of bytes in the String's data because those extra bytes that pad to a boundary
in a ByteArray would be misinterpreted in some Encodings.

Essentially, the more Encoding-aware CharArray became, the more it was just a
String under String. So we removed it.
Marshal Encoding as an attribute of String for compile cache.

Process encoding files is sorted order.

defined. Since Linux filesystems are typically unsorted (I know, what
fucking century, right?!), we manually sort the files.

7146 (Update timestamps when deleting a biblio)

Currently, when you delete an item, the timestamp column in deleteditems is
updated with current time. (This comes from an [unintentional] additional
update statement in DelItem.) It makes deletion time visible.
In the past, the marcxml was updated too at that moment, resulting in an
updated timestamp in biblioitems too. The timestamp in biblio was not touched.

If you delete a biblio however, the timestamps in deletedbiblio and
deletedbiblioitems do not reflect time of deletion. They still show the time of
last update before the record was deleted. This last update can be extracted
from MARC field 005 too.

This behavior is not consistent nor logical. I would suggest to add a statement
in DelBiblio to force updating the timestamp in deletedbiblio(items) too. It
makes the time of deletion visible in the record too. The time of deletion of a
biblio can be very useful for e.g. synchronizing purposes.

issue.title: High memory use when trimming a large RAID1 partition
issue.body:
Memory use gets really high when trimming RAID with two SSD drives and a lot of free space. Python also crashed with some internal double free errors when trying to trim using a file as large as 40 GB. I have successfully tested the program up to 30 GB temporary file sizes and it needed about 4 GB of RAM.

I was able to work around this by removing temporary file deletion from the code and using several ~10 GB files sequentially until I run out of disk space. Then I just removed all the trimmed temporary files at the end. This seemed to restore my write speeds to original performance level.

Additional benefit of using several smaller files is that the disk is almost full for shorter amount of time as checking of the last piece takes less time now.

comment.body: That is much better. Memory use in my case was down to 184 MB when using ~50 GB temporary file. With less things to track, it was much faster as well.

issue.title: Direct messages to the bot should be subscribable without chasing the bot's nick
issue.body:
Right now the PRIVMSG event broadcasts out the target of the message directly in the subscription portion of the message. To subscribe to only direct messages to the bot one would have to subscribe to a pattern similar to: `:PRIVMSG :MENTION` and then preform a logic operation to determine if the target of the message matches the `self` parameter of the message.

Instead, we could transform the subscription component of the message to replace any target matching the bot's nick with a sentinel value so that a subscription to just private messages would look like `ZMQ_SUBSCRIBE,  ":PRIVMSG :MENTION :DIRECT"` and any messages passing by with a channel mentioned should pass by the filter.

Codes will be attached soonish.

Add the todo model

This model will represent one item in our checklist.
It currently doesn't contain a state for tracking if it's checked
or not, instead we use the approach that if it's in the list it's
still unfinished.

The model contains only one field which is 'content' of type string.

Here is a brief description of each file:
 - app/model/todo.rb: Here will any customization to the model be.
 - db/migrate/20111225210412_create_todo.rb - The migration for
   creating the table that the todo will be stored in.
 - test/fixtures/todos.yml - Contains test data.
 - test/unit/todo_test.rb - Contains tests for the model.

Generated using 'rails generate model Todo content:string'.

Add the database schema

This file is an automatically generated file that is created/updated
when you migrate your database. It will contain the current structure
of your database.

The database was migrated using 'rake db:migrate'.

Add the todos controller

This controller will handle all requests regarding the todo model.
These requests include listing, adding, editing and deleting todos.

Here is a brief description of each created file:
 - app/assets/javascripts/todos.js.coffee - Contains the CoffeeScript
   that is specific to the todos controller.
 - app/assets/stylesheets/todos.css.scss - Contains the SCSS that is
   specific to the todos controller.
 - app/controllers/todos_controller.rb - The controller itself. This
   file will contain all the logic relevant to fetching one or more
   models.
 - app/helpers/todos_helper.rb - Helper functions that will be
   available to the views for this todo controller.
   Creating helpers is a good way of removing logic from a view.
 - test/functional/todos_controller_test.rb - Functional tests for
   the todos controller.
 - test/unit/helpers/todos_helper_test.rb - Tests for the todo
   controller helpers.

It was generated using 'rails generate controller Todos'.
Note that it is very important that the controller name
is in plural.

Add the index action of the todos controller

This action will later be responsible for fetching all the todos
in the list.

Currently it does nothing.

Map the root route to todos#index

This will be the home, and only, page of our application.
The root route is the / URL which usually is the entry point in
an application.

Remove the default, static, html file in the public folder

The index.html file is special because is serves as the root route
even if one is already defined.
This is because files in the public/ folder have priority over
routes.

Make the index action fetch all todos

The todos are stored in the @todos variable (accessible by the view).
They have the default ordering (creation date).

Add a view for the root route

Since the index action of the todos controller had no view an
exception was raised when the route was accessed.
To remedy this a view has been added.
This view displays a simple unordered list of all the todos.

Write the create action of the todos controller

This action creates a new todos and redirects to the root view.

Write the update action of the todos controller

This action modifies an existing todo and redirects to the root view.

issue.title: More stream-lined approach to wrap extension points
issue.body:
Jenkins defines two kinds of extension points. One is for thing like Builder and Publisher, where we get a lot of instances created and retained in a single JVM. This is `Descriptor` and `Describable` and we've already got a proven mechanism to define more wrappers.

The other kind, which is actually more fundamental, is a mechanism for Jenkins to discover singleton instances that are the extension points, such as `EnvironmentContributor`, `RunListener`, and `PageDecorator` (`Descriptor` is actually just one of these, and `Describable` is just a further layer above.)

This pull request adds a mechanism for us to rapidly define such singleton extension points.

The main change is the `ExtensionPoint` module, which is a mix-in that detects subtype implementations, and it'll invoke a callback specified via the `when_implemented` class method. I've added a couple of actual wrappers based on this mechanism (and used them successfuly in the RVM plugin.)

One thing that I couldn't quite figure out was how to modify `Jenkins::Model::Describable` to use `ExtensionPoint` to avoid dupliation of the subtype detection logic. I'll think more about it later.

Added raise to Game_Interpreter and history to raise.

History allows for tracking when changes are done to attributes. This can be used for capturing repeatable (and exploitable) events, or if you want to have the impact of changes vary over time (e.g. each change can have a different impact on the attribute based on how long ago it happened).

Game_Troop
  setup_battle_event - will now pass the page for events played out

Game_Event
:page_id
  The current page of the event. This is made available for the Game_Interpreter to read, but will also be passed to the interpreter when the event autoruns.

Game_Interpreter
@page_id
  The current page number of the event being run
:raise(attribute, amount, max[, custom_context])
  Retrieves the context (map_id, event_id, page_id) + passed custom_context, and passes it on to the player's :raise method. Player is considered the leader of the game_party.
  Can be called using the script event command.

    raise("pervert", 1, 50) # add 1 to perversion, up to 50
    raise("pervert", 3, 60, "mySpecialContext") # add 3 to perversion, up to 60, for context "mySpecialContext"

Game_actor
:raise(attribute, amount, max[, context])
  context - value that uniquely identifies the attribute raise.
  If there's a history of the context used for raising the attribute before, it will lessen the change by the number of times called (2 times = delta / 2, 3 times = delta/3 and so on) until the it reaches 1, which will change the delta to 0.
:attribute_history
  ... is a hash containing changes through raise. Key is the context [map_id, event_id, page_id], and the value is when it happened in game time (in seconds).

Index (where on the page the script call is) is not used by default for
the context, since it may give you faulty result during development (where
the page position of the command may change). If it's known that the event's won't change, then having it would be better, because it wouldn't interfere in those cases where one page can do a number of changes to the same attribute (and you don't want to lose context). A workaround is to add a custom context by e.g. adding a digit.

    def wear_plugged_tail(do_wear) # script command on an event's page
      if do_wear
        raise("pervert", 5, 50, 1) # Add 5, up to 50, for context 1
      else
        raise("pervert", 3, 50, 2) # Add 5, up to 50, for context 2
      end
    end

    actor.pervert = 0
    wear_plugged_tail(false) # don't wear
      => 3 # pervert raised by 3 = 3 / 1
    wear_plugged_tail(true) # do wear
      => 8 # pervert raised by 5 = 5 / 1
    wear_plugged_tail(true) # do wear
      => 10 # pervert raised by 2 = 5 / 2

The extra context will only extend the existing contest (map, event, page)
so it can only be used to (un)link raise commands on a page.

Syntax for quasiquotes (ALREADY DECENT QUALITY!)

In line with Martin's SID "String interpolation and formatting", I've implemented a syntax for qq's:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NdxNxZYodPA-c4MLr33KzwzKFkzm9iW9POexT9PkJsU/edit?hl=en_US

The machinery described in the SID has been generalized to allow for
arbitrary quasiquotes, not only for string interpolations.

The main difference from the proposal is using the newly introduced Quasiquote class from scala.reflect:
  class Quasiquote(parts: List[String], splices: List[Code[_]], formats: List[String])
and transforming quasiquotes into an intermediate representation that involves Quasiquote and that
can be processed in a domain-specific way later on, by a quasiquoting macro.

For example,
  s"hello $s"
will be transformed into
  val parts = Apply(Ident(ListModule), List(Literal(Constant("hello ")), Literal(Constant(""))))
  val splices = Apply(Ident(ListModule), Ident(newTermName("s")))
  val formats = Apply(Ident(ListModule), List(Literal(Constant(""))))
  val ctor = New(Ident(QuasiquoteLiteralClass), List(parts, splices, formats))
  Apply(Select(ctor, newTermName("s")), List())

In this commit, I've injected a hack into doTypedApply that detects calls to s()
and manually assembles string interpolation logic. Later on, the typer will resolve "s"
to be an extension macro for Quasiquote and will invoke that macro, which, in its turn,
will produce the glue that involves StringContext and Formatted as mentioned in the SID.

issue.title: Some authors of one-file plugins are not creating repository with correct directory tree
issue.body:
You can find these plugins by searching for `scm.*archive` in `plugin/vim-addon-manager-known-repositories.vim` file. Currently they are added with code like

This issue is to discuss what should be done with them (first is the most prefered):

1. Add postinstall and postupdate hooks and create normal directory structure with them.
2. Use raw file url (like above).
3. Ignore them.
4. Add code that is able to checkout into `plugin_root_dir/subdirectory`.

First is prefered because these hooks will also be used to run additional commands if required (for example, `Command-T` installation and update does require running `ruby extconf.rb && make`) and also deal with other violations (like putting doc and plugin into the root directory) which can’t be dealt with fourth solution. Second just looks like a hack and makes plugin unconditionally updated. Third is bad because it makes VAM support less plugins which can’t be good from my point of view. Fourth is a hack too, but it is to be added to another place.

issue.title: scrollbar.js
issue.body:
I'd like to see a “scrollbar” plugin, that provides a visual representation of how much of a particular conversation you are looking at. That is, the ratio of the hilighted portion at the bottom of the vertical bar to the height of the entire bar should represent the ratio of the visible chat-area to the last period of time with, on average, as much activity as is visible in the chat area.

- if there's mouse support in the terminal, clicking on the bar should move you to that location
- if you were hilighted at points further back in the history, those points should have lines of some sort on the scrollbar
- the portion of the whole scrollback represented by the height of the scrollbar should be dynamically decided based on the quantity of activity inside the visible chat area; that is, if you're looking at the tail-end of a very fast-paced, active conversation (i.e. “one message every fifteen seconds, average,”) then the scrollbar should be tall enough to represent the period of time during which the chatroom has been that active, on average (no extended periods silence.)
- might be able to utilize this to dictate how much scrollback we dynamically load from the Hub on a freshly opened petal

----

- Might be able to integrate with some of the [threading](/elliottcable/-_-/issues/12) work, to determine the height of the scrollbar based on the active “conversations?”

comment.body:
@eboyjr er, nah. Not sure how else to explain it …

Basically, the vertical bar wouldn't represent *the entire scrollback*, which is completely useless information (the user doesn't care how much scroll back we happen to have loaded; or, alternatively, if you would rather it show *all* scroll back the server knows about, then many channels would have bars representing *years* of scrollback. Neither provides useful information to the user).

Instead, it would represent, as much as possible, the current day/conversation/topic/period-of-activity. *That* is useful information.

“This much of the current activity-period is visible in your window, and you're scrolled <this> far up into it with <that> much new material below the point you're scrolled up to,” represented by a vertical equivalent of `[                    ██       ]`

Rewrite variable handling in generated parsers

Before this commit, variables for saving match results and parse
positions in generated parsers were not used efficiently. Each rule
basically used its own variable(s) for storing the data, with names
generated sequentially during code emitting. There was no reuse of
variables and a lot of unnecessary assignments between them.

It is easy to see that both match results and parse positions can
actually be stored on a stack that grows as the parser walks deeper in
the grammar tree and shrinks as it returns. Moreover, if one creates a
new stack for each rule the parser enters, its maximum depth can be
computed statically from the grammar. This allows us to implement the
stack not as an array, but as a set of numbered variables in each
function that handles parsing of a grammar rule, avoiding potentially
slow array accesses.

separate stack for match results and for parse positions. As a result,
defined variables are reused and unnecessary copying avoided.

KVM: Device assignment permission checks

Only allow KVM device assignment to attach to devices which:

 - Are not bridges
 - Have BAR resources (assume others are special devices)
 - The user has permissions to use

Assigning a bridge is a configuration error, it's not supported, and
typically doesn't result in the behavior the user is expecting anyway.
Devices without BAR resources are typically chipset components that
also don't have host drivers.  We don't want users to hold such devices
captive or cause system problems by fencing them off into an iommu
domain.  We determine "permission to use" by testing whether the user
has access to the PCI sysfs resource files.  By default a normal user
will not have access to these files, so it provides a good indication
that an administration agent has granted the user access to the device.

KVM: Don't automatically expose the TSC deadline timer in cpuid

Unlike all of the other cpuid bits, the TSC deadline timer bit is set
unconditionally, regardless of what userspace wants.

This is broken in several ways:
 - if userspace doesn't use KVM_CREATE_IRQCHIP, and doesn't emulate the TSC
   deadline timer feature, a guest that uses the feature will break
 - live migration to older host kernels that don't support the TSC deadline
   timer will cause the feature to be pulled from under the guest's feet;
   breaking it
 - guests that are broken wrt the feature will fail.

Fix by not enabling the feature automatically; instead report it to userspace.
Because the feature depends on KVM_CREATE_IRQCHIP, which we cannot guarantee
will be called, we expose it via a KVM_CAP_TSC_DEADLINE_TIMER and not
KVM_GET_SUPPORTED_CPUID.

Fixes the Illumos guest kernel, which uses the TSC deadline timer feature.

inprogress lease breaks") introduced a possible error pointer
dereference on failure to allocate memory.  locks_conflict() will
dereference the passed-in new lease lock structure that may be an error pointer.

pull_request.body:
These libraries, which are an artifact of the ZoL development
process, conflict with packages that are already in distribution:

  * libspl: SPL Programming Language
  * libavl: AVL for Linux
  * libefi: GRUB

And these libraries are potential conflicts:

  * libshare: the Linux Mount Manager
  * libunicode: Perl and Python

Recompose these five ZoL components into the four libraries that are
conventionally provided by Solaris and FreeBSD systems:

  + libnvpair
  + libuutil
  + libzpool
  + libzfs

This change resolves the name conflict, makes ZoL more compatible
with existing software that uses autotools to detect ZFS, and allows
pkg-zfs to better reflect the official Debian kFreeBSD packaging.

Closes: #430

issue.title: Problems of {plugin}[{snr}] naming scheme
issue.body:
I just realized that this scheme contains at least three problems:

1. Addition of new plugin (renaming some of old plugins) with name matching old one will leave old plugin without updates.
2. Renaming of some plugin will leave existing installations being not updated automatically anymore.
3. You can make user update plugin with `name={plugin1}{snr1}` with plugin with `name={plugin2}={plugin1}{snr1}` if `{snr2}<{snr1}` (opposite leads to garbage names (`{plugin}{snr}{snr}`)).

Do you have some statistics about how often does this happen and whether it is worth working on (first two, third is vulnerability and must be fixed)? I suggest

1. Duplicating of just `{plugin}` entries with `{plugin}%{snr}` (easy), so one can always use persistent name.
2. Having a renames file which will create warnings if you try to update renamed plugin.
3. Replacing `{plugin}{snr}` scheme with `{plugin}%{snr}` as percent sign is not allowed to be in plugin names, but allowed in file names on windows (easy, but breaks compatibility). Another solution is to make script check whether newly created names is already taken, but this leads to garbage names (names with duplicate `{snr}` parts) as well.

comment.body:
It may be better if users would be able to pass names `{name}%{snr}` or `%{snr}`: first to force check on matching script number and second to select plugin by its script number as it is the only persistent property of the plugin. Per cent sign will thus be reserved and forbidden in plugin names, but it is not a loss as it is not currently used. For plugins not posted on vim.org this is `{name}%{URL}`/`%{URL}`. It will prevent downloading plugins from untrusted source in cases like “author renamed plugin and then bad guy created malware plugin named identical to old normal plugin name”.

// By the way, what should be used instead of “bad guy” here? In Russian it is “злоумышленник” which is translated as “malefactor, deliberate criminal; culprit”, but I like neither of these translations.
